			<title>Robot Cars and Ethics</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?78729-Robot-Cars-and-Ethics&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Wed, 01 Jun 2016 16:20:44 GMT</pubDate>
			<description><![CDATA[https://nplusonemag.com/online-only/online-only/the-amorality-of-self-driving-cars/ 
 
This is a really good article about the coming of the self-driving "robot" car and built in ethics.  I really like the part about Vision Zero and their belief:  No amount of mobility or economic efficiency is...]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div><a href="https://nplusonemag.com/online-only/online-only/the-amorality-of-self-driving-cars/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://nplusonemag.com/online-only/...-driving-cars/</a><br />
<br />
This is a really good article about the coming of the self-driving &quot;robot&quot; car and built in ethics.  I really like the part about Vision Zero and their belief:  <i>No amount of mobility or economic efficiency is worth a single human life</i>.  As hard as it is to imagine no automobile deaths, it is definitely a worthy goal to pursue.<br />
<br />
I have to agree with the whole idea about how do you code into a self-driving car who to kill when it determines an accident it imminent.  I think the below quote from the article is a bit of an exaggeration, but still valid.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_description">Quote:</div>
	<div class="bbcode_quote printable">
		<hr />
		
			In the “The Tunnel Problem,” Millar’s driverless car (let’s call her Porsche again) is fast approaching a narrow tunnel, the entrance of which is blocked by a child who has fallen in the roadway. The car can either kill the kid or hit the wall of the tunnel, killing the driver (who is really just a passenger).Millar insists programmers need to build such scenarios into their code. I imagine them writing something like this:<br />
if (kid_in_tunnel &gt; 16) {<br />
  kill kid_in_tunnel;<br />
lp “We are sorry for your loss.”;<br />
}<br />
 else {<br />
  kill ass_in_Porsche;<br />
lp “Serves you right, schmucko.”;<br />
}<br />
Millar wants programmers to ask, “How should the car react?” But again, there’s a better question: “Why was the car going so damn fast in the first place?”
			
		<hr />
	</div>
</div>I for one am really torn on the whole coming of the robot car.  On the one hand I would love an autopilot when I have to drive a long way on a boring interstate highway (although with audio books even that is no longer as bad as it use to be), but on the other hand (and I know you will be able to disengage autopilot mode) I love to drive on challenging, fun roads.  Driving is like a lot of other things in life, at times it's a chore, but often it can be freeing and fun.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
